==Countries affected==
  â
Similar protests actually took place in almost all Arab countries<ref>{{cite web|author=By AA Sheikh |url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/121796/the-potato-revolution/ |title=The potato revolution â The Express Tribune |publisher=Tribune.com.pk |date=2011-02-19 |accessdate=2011-02-23}}</ref> from [[Morocco]] to [[Iraq]], as well as in other states, ranging from [[Gabon]] to [[Albania]], [[Iran]] and [[Kazakhstan]], to [[China]]. China has censored most media coverage of the Arab worldâs popular revolt of the last few weeks<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/jasmine-revolution-coverage-censored-china-159665 |title='Jasmine Revolution' Coverage Censored in China |publisher=The Hollywood Reporter |date= |accessdate=2011-02-23}}</ref> leading to difficulty in organizing Jasmine protests in China.<ref>{{cite web|author=ByÂ  Jaime FlorCruz, CNN |url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/asiapcf/02/20/china.protests/ |title='Jasmine' protests in China fall flat |publisher=CNN.com |date= |accessdate=2011-02-23}}</ref>
  â   â
===Iran===
  â
Supporters of the Green Movement gathered in scattered groups for the second time within a week to denounce the death of Saane Zhaleh, 26, and Mohammadi Mokhtari, 22, who were killed in Tehran on Monday. An opposition website affiliated to Mehdi Karroubi, a former presidential candidate, said that one person had been killed in Haft-e-Tir square in central Tehran when security forces opened fire at protesters. Dozens were arrested.
  â   â
===Algeria===
  â
Police thwarted a rally by thousands of pro-democracy supporters, breaking up the crowd into isolated groups to keep them from marching. Algerian opposition leader Tahar Besbes was badly injured during a pro-democracy rally when riot police clashed with protesters. <ref name="businessinsider1"/>
  â   â
===Yemen===
  â
The leader of Yemen's secessionist Southern Movement, Hasan Baoum, was arrested by an "armed military group" in an Aden hospital, according to his son, and shots were fired at a demonstration in the capital Sana'a, as unrest continued for a ninth consecutive day.
  â
===Morocco===
  â
Thousands took to the streets of Rabat, Casablanca, Tangier and Marrakech in peaceful protests demanding a new constitution, a change in government and an end to corruption. During a march on Hassan II Avenue in the capital, Rabat, demonstrators demanded a new constitution to bring more democracy to the country. They shouted slogans calling for economic opportunity, education reform, better health services, and help in coping with the rising cost of living.
  â   â
The Associated Press estimated the turnout in Rabat at 4,000. Organizers put the crowd outside Parliament at 20,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boston.com/news/world/africa/articles/2011/02/21/moroccans_join_in_spreading_unrest |title=Moroccans join in spreading unrest - The Boston Globe |publisher=Boston.com |date= |accessdate=2011-02-23}}</ref> The people were calling for a reduction in King Mohammed VIâs powers, better health services and reduced living costs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metro.co.uk/news/856068-protests-spread-to-streets-of-morocco |title=Protests spread to streets of Morocco |publisher=Metro.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2011-02-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.euronews.net/2011/02/20/moroccans-want-to-reign-in-royal-powers/ |title=Moroccans want to reign in royal powers | euronews, world news |publisher=Euronews.net |date= |accessdate=2011-02-23}}</ref>
  â   â
===Libya===
  â   â
The Jasime Revolution also erupted in the country of Libya where enraged dissidents and the government are currently embroiled in titanic violence which has led to the freezing of the assets of Libyaâs leaders including Qaddafi and the withdrawal of oil companies from the country.
  â
Angry Demonstrators Call for Libya's Gadaffi to Step Down.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.yahoo.com/s/ac/20110216/pl_ac/7872960_angry_demonstrators_call_for_libyas_gadaffi_to_step_down |title=Angry Demonstrators Call for Libya's Gadaffi to Step Down - Yahoo! News |publisher=News.yahoo.com |date=2011-02-16 |accessdate=2011-02-23}}</ref>
  â
Libya's security forces may yet manage to put down the demonstrations, as they did with a smaller upsurge in 2006, although that is looking increasingly unlikely as the violence spreads and escalates. Eyewitnesses speak of how the Libyan people appear to have lost their fear - and this is a regime more brutal and absolute than the one that was toppled in Egypt earlier this month.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/standard/article-23925145-libyan-uprising-risks-red-faces-in-whitehall.do |title=Libyan uprising risks red faces in Whitehall | News |publisher=Thisislondon.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2011-02-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/Second-wave-of-sandstorm/Article1-665188.aspx |title=Second wave of sandstorm |publisher=Hindustan Times |date= |accessdate=2011-02-23}}</ref>
  â   â
===Oman===
  â   â
Oman protesters called for democracy, about 300 people protested and demanded political reforms and better pay in a peaceful way. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/NewsContent/3/12/5923/Business/Economy/Oman-protesters-call-for-democracy,-more-jobs.aspx |title=Oman protesters call for democracy, more jobs - Economy - Business - Ahram Online |publisher=English.ahram.org.eg |date=2011-02-19 |accessdate=2011-02-23}}</ref>
